				<!-- -->
				<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="544"> 
					<tr>
						<td><b>Ingredients</b></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr>
						<td>2 pears, 2 whole gingers, 50 whole black peppers, sugar 1 C, water 4 C, pine nuts 2 Tbsp</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="20" border="0"></td></tr>
				</table>
				
				<!-- -->
				<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="544"> 
					<tr>
						<td colspan="2"><b>Directions</b></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td width="15">1)</td>
						<td>Pare the ginger, cut it into thin slices, and put into boiling water. When the flavor is soaked out, add sugar.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>2)</td>
						<td>Cut the pear into 6~8 pieces, depending on its size. Peel, pit, and round the edge.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>3)</td>
						<td>On the smooth surface of the pear's backside, wedge 2~3 whole peppers. Simmer in sugary water.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>4)</td>
						<td>When flavors are mixed well, take the ginger flakes out. Put the pear and liquid in a bowl. Garnish with pine nuts.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
				</table>
				<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="544">
					<tr valign="top">
						<td width="10" class="o">*</td>
						<td class="o">Unlike the cooking style of the noble family in the past, the procedure of rounding the pear is sometimes omitted these days. It is sliced into 6~8 pieces, the pieces are cut in half, and cooked with a few peppers wedged in them.</td>
